The paper deals with parameterized algorithms for problems on directed graphs, which suggests that it could belong to categories related to graph theory and algorithms. The use of obstruction theorems and kernelization techniques also points towards categories such as cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics). The mention of planar graphs and minor-excluded graphs suggests categories such as cs.CG (Computational Geometry) and cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory). Finally, the use of a layering technique similar to the one used by Baker to obtain PTAS suggests a possible connection to cs.CC (Computational Complexity).
